[Comment "short-sweet-the-italian-game/course/4999, variation/180282"]

1. e4 {[%cal Bd2d4][%csl Gd4,Ge4] White's most popular first move attracts World 
champions and novices alike. Chess newcomers naturally gravitate towards it 
while many World Championships were decided by it. Fischer's move, together with 
1. d4, has the simple plan of taking over the whole centre by playing d4 on the 
next move. In addition, it opens lines for White's bishop and queen, while 
preparing rapid development and kingside castling.} e5 {Black avoids the wild, 
unbalanced Sicilian or the exotic French and Caro-Kann and instead heads for the 
solid Open Games.} 2. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3e5][%csl Re5] A natural move - White attacks 
e5 and develops. By developing his kingside knight, White is one move closer to 
short castling.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e5]} ({Black replies similarly - he covers the 
pawn and develops. However, Black has other options at his disposal - most 
notably} 2... Nf6 {, the Petroff Defence,}) ({and} 2... d6 {, the Philidor 
Defence. Both of these openings will be covered in the final lines of this 
course.}) 3. Bc4 {The Italian Game is one of the oldest opening in chess and a 
staple amongst novice players. Despite this, it has recently been utilised by 
some of the top players in the World, including Magnus Carlsen. With 3. Bc4, 
White can expect to get a safe, positional game without being forced to learn 
all the theory in the Ruy Lopez. White's general plan is simple - central play 
with d4. It is important to note that this doesn't come immediately - instead 
White should prepare this pawn break with c3 and take his time in executing it. 
Often White will develop fully before setting his central pawns into motion.} 
({From this position, Black has 2 main options:} 3. Bc4 3... Bc5) ({and} 3. Bc4 
3... Nf6 {. The former usually leads to quiet positions while the later invites 
White to take play into the unorthodox with} 4. Ng5 {.}) {First I will cover 
some rare deviations, such as 3... g6 and 3... Nd4. These are not very 
dangerous, but it is useful to have a vague idea of what to do against them. 
Other rare moves like 3... h6 and 3... Be7 are bound to transpose to the other 
lines I cover.} Nd4 $6 {[%cal Bf3e5,Bd8g5,Gg5e5,Gg5g2] This isn't much more than 
a beginner's trap.} 4. Nxd4 ({It is important to remember not to take on e5, as} 
4. Nxe5 $2 {runs into} Qg5 {. Instead, White can now obtain a nice, clear 
advantage.}) exd4 5. O-O {[%cal Bc2c3][%csl Gg1]} d6 6. c3 dxc3 7. Nxc3 $18 
{[%cal Bd2d4][%csl Gc3,Gc4] White's development lead out of the opening is 
crushing.} *

