1. e4 {White's most popular first move attracts World champions and novices 
alike. Chess newcomers naturally gravitate towards it while many World 
Championships were decided by it. Fischer's move, together with 1. d4, has the 
simple plan of taking over the whole centre by playing d4 on the next move. In 
addition, it opens lines for White's bishop and queen, while preparing rapid 
development and kingside castling.} e5 {Black avoids the wild, unbalanced 
Sicilian or the exotic French and Caro-Kann and instead heads for the solid Open 
Games.} 2. Nf3 {A natural move - White attacks e5 and develops. By developing 
his kingside knight, White is one move closer to short castling.} Nc6 ({Black 
replies similarly - he covers the pawn and develops. However, Black has other 
options at his disposal - most notably} 2... Nf6 {, the Petroff Defence,}) 
({and} 2... d6 {, the Philidor Defence. Both of these openings will be covered 
in the final lines of this course.}) 3. Bc4 {The Italian Game is one of the 
oldest opening in chess and a staple amongst novice players. Despite this, it 
has recently been utilised by some of the top players in the World, including 
Magnus Carlsen. With 3. Bc4, White can expect to get a safe, positional game 
without being forced to learn all the theory in the Ruy Lopez. White's general 
plan is simple - central play with d4. It is important to note that this doesn't 
come immediately - instead White should prepare this pawn break with c3 and take 
his time in executing it. Often White will develop fully before setting his 
central pawns into motion.} ({From this position, Black has 2 main options:} 3. 
Bc4 3... Bc5) ({and} 3. Bc4 3... Nf6 {. The former usually leads to quiet 
positions while the later invites White to take play into the unorthodox with} 
4. Ng5 {.}) {First I will cover some rare deviations, such as 3... g6 and 3... 
Nd4. These are not very dangerous, but it is useful to have a vague idea of what 
to do against them. Other rare moves like 3... h6 and 3... Be7 are bound to 
transpose to the other lines I cover.} Bc5 {[%cal Bg8f6,Be8g8][%csl Gc5] Of 
Black's two most popular moves here, this one is regarded as the 'quieter' one. 
Black plays simply - he develops his bishop, just like White, and doesn't allow 
White any funny tactical possibilities.} 4. O-O {[%cal Bd2d3,Bc2c3]} ({In an 
opening as flexible as the Italian, naturally both sides have a number of 
different plans at their disposal and a huge amount of possible move orders to 
carry out their plans. Originally I looked at ideas of} 4. c3 {and 5. d3, which 
delayed castling so that White can develop his second knight, but I eventually 
discarded this because I wasn't thrilled with the positions that resulted after 
an early ...d5.}) {Instead I opted for 4. O-O - this aims to prevent an early 
...d5. If Black attempts to follow-through with this, the e-pawn will come under 
immense pressure and he stands a good chance of getting blown away in the centre 
(since our rook can quickly come to the e-file). The line I eventually settled 
on is similar to my choice for 3... Nf6 - White's plan is to put a focus on a 
queenside expansion with a4 and b4. As we'll see, in the main line 7. a4 has 
been in vogue (as of 2016) with Carlsen even utilising it in a World 
Championship match.} Nf6 {Black develops naturally - he doesn't really have any 
decent alternatives.} 5. d3 {[%cal Gd3e4][%csl Ge4] We protect e4 with a pawn. 
Unfortunately, protecting the e4-pawn solely with the rook on e1 is bound to run 
into some tactical problems with ...Nxe4 followed by ...d5.} d6 ({Black foregoes 
any attempt to play the ...d5 break and settles for the more modest ...d6. This 
supports the e5 pawn and prepares to develop Black's light-squared bishop. 
After} 5... O-O {, White has a number of options including 6. Bg5, but my choice 
for consistency is} 6. a4 {, which also happened to be Carlsen's choice. Play is 
very likely to transpose into the main line.}) 6. c3 {[%cal Bb2b4,Bd3d4] With 
Black having renounced his ...d5 ambitions, we can safely continue with our own 
central and queenside play. c3 is a normal move which helps prepare the b4 and 
d4 advances.} O-O {The most natural move. If Black opts for the main alternative 
of a6, we'll continue with 7. a4 anyway - the game is bound to transpose into 
one of the lines I've covered here.} 7. a4 {[%cal Gc4a2,Bb2b4,Ba4a5][%csl 
Rc5,Ga2] This is an interesting multi-purpose move which has caught on recently 
at the top-level. It is fresh, interesting and as good a try as any for an 
advantage in the Italian. That's why it's my choice for the repertoire - but why 
is it played? This move serves two main roles: 1. The bishop is provided with an 
escape square in preparation for any black ...Na5 idea (which tries to gain the 
bishop pair). 2. a4 aids White in his queenside expansion. It threatens b4 + a5, 
trapping Black's bishop, and has the additional threat of a4-a5-a6. b4 is simply 
stronger now that a4 has been played.} a5 {[%cal Gc5a7,Ga5b4][%csl Ga7] This is 
the most forceful way in which Black can try prevent White's queenside 
expansion. Black frees a square for his bishop and prevents b4 (for now). On the 
whole, however, I think the inclusion of a4 and ...a5 favours White. Previously 
Black had the idea of ...Na5 at his disposal (White didn't have an equivalent 
idea) which is no longer possible. On the flip side, White needs to work a lot 
harder to push through b4. However, if White achieves this pawn break, it will 
be much more powerful than it would've been otherwise. I recommend that White 
switches over to play a bit more in the centre - we'll develop and see what 
Black does.} 8. Bg5 {[%csl Gg5] A good, active square for the bishop.} h6 9. Bh4 
$14 {[%cal Gh4d8,Bb1d2,Bf1e1,Bh2h3][%csl Rf6] Black has a fairly difficult 
choice to make in this position: whether or not to play ...g5. On the one hand 
...g5 shuts down our bishop, but on the other it weakens Black's kingside in the 
long run which White can exploit. White also has the very decent option of 
sacrificing his knight for Black's 2 kingside pawns - even though this is far 
from a direct win or anything, it appears very interesting and double-edged, 
with great practical chances for White due to Black's non-existent king shelter. 
If Black refrains from ...g5, White should continue with the 'usual' moves - h3, 
Re1, Nbd2, etc. with the hope of eventually carrying out the d4 break.} *

