Sicilian or the exotic French and Caro-Kann and instead heads for the solid Open 
Games.} 2. Nf3 {A natural move - White attacks e5 and develops. By developing 
his kingside knight, White is one move closer to short castling.} Nc6 ({Black 
replies similarly - he covers the pawn and develops. However, Black has other 
options at his disposal - most notably} 2... Nf6 {, the Petroff Defence,}) 
({and} 2... d6 {, the Philidor Defence. Both of these openings will be covered 
in the final lines of this course.}) 3. Bc4 {The Italian Game is one of the 
oldest opening in chess and a staple amongst novice players. Despite this, it 
has recently been utilised by some of the top players in the World, including 
Magnus Carlsen. With 3. Bc4, White can expect to get a safe, positional game 
without being forced to learn all the theory in the Ruy Lopez. White's general 
plan is simple - central play with d4. It is important to note that this doesn't 
come immediately - instead White should prepare this pawn break with c3 and take 
his time in executing it. Often White will develop fully before setting his 
central pawns into motion.} ({From this position, Black has 2 main options:} 3. 
Bc4 3... Bc5) ({and} 3. Bc4 3... Nf6 {. The former usually leads to quiet 
positions while the later invites White to take play into the unorthodox with} 
4. Ng5 {.}) {First I will cover some rare deviations, such as 3... g6 and 3... 
Nd4. These are not very dangerous, but it is useful to have a vague idea of what 
to do against them. Other rare moves like 3... h6 and 3... Be7 are bound to 
transpose to the other lines I cover.} Bc5 {Of Black's two most popular moves 
here, this one is regarded as the 'quieter' one. Black plays simply - he 
develops his bishop, just like White, and doesn't allow White any funny tactical 
possibilities.} 4. O-O ({In an opening as flexible as the Italian, naturally 
both sides have a number of different plans at their disposal and a huge amount 
of possible move orders to carry out their plans. Originally I looked at ideas 
of} 4. c3 {and 5. d3, which delayed castling so that White can develop his 
second knight, but I eventually discarded this because I wasn't thrilled with 
the positions that resulted after an early ...d5.}) {Instead I opted for 4. O-O 
- this aims to prevent an early ...d5. If Black attempts to follow-through with 
this, the e-pawn will come under immense pressure and he stands a good chance of 
getting blown away in the centre (since our rook can quickly come to the 
e-file). The line I eventually settled on is similar to my choice for 3... Nf6 - 
White's plan is to put a focus on a queenside expansion with a4 and b4. As we'll 
see, in the main line 7. a4 has been in vogue (as of 2016) with Carlsen even 
utilising it in a World Championship match.} Nf6 {Black develops naturally - he 
doesn't really have any decent alternatives.} 5. d3 {We protect e4 with a pawn. 
Unfortunately, protecting the e4-pawn solely with the rook on e1 is bound to run 
into some tactical problems with ...Nxe4 followed by ...d5.} d6 ({Black foregoes 
any attempt to play the ...d5 break and settles for the more modest ...d6. This 
supports the e5 pawn and prepares to develop Black's light-squared bishop. 
After} 5... O-O {, White has a number of options including 6. Bg5, but my choice 
for consistency is} 6. a4 {, which also happened to be Carlsen's choice. Play is 
very likely to transpose into the main line.}) 6. c3 {[%cal Bb2b4,Bd3d4] With 
Black having renounced his ...d5 ambitions, we can safely continue with our own 
central and queenside play. c3 is a normal move which helps prepare the b4 and 
d4 advances.} O-O {The most natural move. If Black opts for the main alternative 
of a6, we'll continue with 7. a4 anyway - the game is bound to transpose into 
one of the lines I've covered here.} 7. a4 {[%cal Bc4a2,Rc6a5,Bb2b4,Ba4a5] This 
is an interesting multi-purpose move which has caught on recently at the 
top-level. It is fresh, interesting and as good a try as any for an advantage in 
the Italian. That's why it's my choice for the repertoire - but why is it 
played? This move serves two main roles: 1. The bishop is provided with an 
escape square in preparation for any black ...Na5 idea (which tries to gain the 
bishop pair). 2. a4 aids White in his queenside expansion. It threatens b4 + a5, 
trapping Black's bishop, and has the additional threat of a4-a5-a6. b4 is simply 
stronger now that a4 has been played.} a6 {[%cal Gc5a7,Bb2b4][%csl Ga7] This is 
a slightly more subtle way to prevent the threat of trapping the bishop with b4 
and a5. Black takes a slightly more laid back approach on the queenside for now, 
but keeps the option of a future ...b5 break for himself open.} 8. b4 {[%csl 
Rc5,Gb4,Ga4] We might as well take the opportunity we've been given to gain some 
queenside space.} Ba7 9. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2e4,Bd3d4] Natural development - White is 
preparing a d4 advance and supports the e4 pawn.} Ne7 {[%cal Be7g6] Black is 
employing a typical manoeuvre which reroutes the knight to g6. This square has 
several advantages over c6: 1. It is less vulnerable to advances such as b4-b5 
or d3-d4-d5. 2. It gets out of the way of the c-pawn which might want to move in 
the future. 3. The knight has better prospects on g6 - it can sometimes go to 
f4, for example.} 10. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e4,Gd2f1][%csl Ge4] This is a standard 
multi-purpose move - White frees up the f1-square for the knight and supports 
e4.} Ng6 11. d4 $11 {[%cal Bc4b3,Bc1b2,Bd1c2,Bh2h3]} ({Naturally this advance 
can be delayed and} 11. h3) ({as well as} 11. Nf1 {are also very good options - 
perhaps they might even be preferable.}) {The text move was the choice of 
Carlsen in his World Championship game against Karjakin. Although the position 
is most likely equal, there is a huge amount of play for both sides. Black 
should try to challenge White in the centre with ...c6 and ...d5 as quickly as 
possible. Otherwise, White will develop and generate queenside play with b5. 
White needs to watch out for tactical tricks like ...Nxe4 followed by ...d5 
(once ...c6 has been played) so dropping the bishop back to d3 or b3 is a decent 
idea. Other normal moves might be Qc2, h3 and Bb2.} *

