[White "5. Italian Game"]
[Black "3... Nf6 and 4... d5"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-italian-game/course/4999, variation/179015"]

1. e4 {White's most popular first move attracts World champions and novices 
alike. Chess newcomers naturally gravitate towards it while many World 
Championships were decided by it. Fischer's move, together with 1. d4, has the 
simple plan of taking over the whole centre by playing d4 on the next move. In 
addition, it opens lines for White's bishop and queen, while preparing rapid 
development and kingside castling.} e5 {Black avoids the wild, unbalanced 
Sicilian or the exotic French and Caro-Kann and instead heads for the solid Open 
Games.} 2. Nf3 {A natural move - White attacks e5 and develops. By developing 
his kingside knight, White is one move closer to short castling.} Nc6 ({Black 
replies similarly - he covers the pawn and develops. However, Black has other 
options at his disposal - most notably} 2... Nf6 {, the Petroff Defence,}) 
({and} 2... d6 {, the Philidor Defence. Both of these openings will be covered 
in the final lines of this course.}) 3. Bc4 {The Italian Game is one of the 
oldest opening in chess and a staple amongst novice players. Despite this, it 
has recently been utilised by some of the top players in the World, including 
Magnus Carlsen. With 3. Bc4, White can expect to get a safe, positional game 
without being forced to learn all the theory in the Ruy Lopez. White's general 
plan is simple - central play with d4. It is important to note that this doesn't 
come immediately - instead White should prepare this pawn break with c3 and take 
his time in executing it. Often White will develop fully before setting his 
central pawns into motion.} ({From this position, Black has 2 main options:} 3. 
Bc4 3... Bc5) ({and} 3. Bc4 3... Nf6 {. The former usually leads to quiet 
positions while the later invites White to take play into the unorthodox with} 
4. Ng5 {.}) {First I will cover some rare deviations, such as 3... g6 and 3... 
Nd4. These are not very dangerous, but it is useful to have a vague idea of what 
to do against them. Other rare moves like 3... h6 and 3... Be7 are bound to 
transpose to the other lines I cover.} Nf6 ({This move is one of the two biggest 
challenges to the Italian game - together with 3 ...Bc5. While 3... Bc5 leads to 
tranquil waters, 3... Nf6 invites complications and imbalances if White obliges. 
White has 2 main choices here:} Nf6 4. d3) ({and} Nf6 4. Ng5 {.}) ({Other 
options such as} Nf6 4. d4) ({and} Nf6 4. Nc3 {are playable as well, but they 
are neither as challenging nor as popular as 4. d3 and 4. Ng5.}) 4. d3 ({For 
this repertoire my choice is 4. d3. The chief alternative,} 4. Ng5 {, was 
examined in depth but I discarded it for a few reasons:}) {1. It is too 
complicated and too theoretical for the purpose of this repertoire. 2. Black 
often relishes the wild positions after 4. Ng5 - he gets the chance to sacrifice 
a pawn for which he usually receives good compensation. 3. Finally, 4. d3 has 
the advantage of building a nice 'bridge' between Bc5 and Nf6. The positions can 
transpose and the structures are similar, meaning the plans and ideas are 
usually applicable to both lines. So, now that I've outlined my reasoning for my 
choice, let's take a look at the variations...} d5 {This central break can be 
dangerous if White is caught unawares, but in this case it is usually Black who 
is unprepared for a more open game. His e5-pawn usually comes under heavy fire 
now that the e-file is opened up.} 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. O-O {[%cal 
Bf1e1,Ge1e5,Gf3e5,Ge5e8,Bc2c3,Bd3d4][%csl Re5,Re8] Black has a handful of 
options at this point, but White's plan is similar - put rapid pressure on the 
e5-pawn and maybe prepare a future central d4 break with c3. Black will often be 
forced to give up the bishop pair by exchanging his light-squared bishop for the 
knight on f3 (...Bc8-g4xf3). If White can induce this, i.e. gain the bishop pair 
free of charge, his opening has been a success.} Be7 7. Re1 {[%cal 
Ge1e5,Gf3e5][%csl Re5] White must pile up the pressure on e5 before Black has a 
chance to unravel and solidifty his space advantage.} Nb6 8. Bb3 {[%csl 
Re5,Gb3]} Bg4 {Black can't hold onto the e5 pawn comfortably without 
surrendering the bishop pair.} 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 $14 {[%cal 
Bb1d2,Bd2c4,Ba2a4,Ba4a5][%csl Gb3,Gc1,Rb6,Re5] White has gained the bishop pair, 
which is great. Next he'll strive to open the position to his advantage. 
Developing the knight to c4 via d2 and advancing the a-pawn forwards (a4-a5) are 
also decent ideas.} *

