tranquil waters, 3... Nf6 invites complications and imbalances if White obliges. 
White has 2 main choices here:} Nf6 4. d3) ({and} Nf6 4. Ng5 {.}) ({Other 
options such as} Nf6 4. d4) ({and} Nf6 4. Nc3 {are playable as well, but they 
are neither as challenging nor as popular as 4. d3 and 4. Ng5.}) 4. d3 {[%cal 
Be1g1,Bh1e1]} ({For this repertoire my choice is 4. d3. The chief alternative,} 
4. Ng5 {, was examined in depth but I discarded it for a few reasons:}) {1. It 
is too complicated and too theoretical for the purpose of this repertoire. 2. 
Black often relishes the wild positions after 4. Ng5 - he gets the chance to 
sacrifice a pawn for which he usually receives good compensation. 3. Finally, 4. 
d3 has the advantage of building a nice 'bridge' between Bc5 and Nf6. The 
positions can transpose and the structures are similar, meaning the plans and 
ideas are usually applicable to both lines. So, now that I've outlined my 
reasoning for my choice, let's take a look at the variations...} Be7 ({From this 
square Black's bishop is less active, but also less vulnerable than on c5. Both 
moves have their trumps, but in this variation play tends to develop along 
similar lines to the Ruy Lopez. Please note that} 4... Bc5 {would transpose to 
the ...Bc5 lines - refer to those lines for coverage of that move.}) 5. O-O {We 
are going to castle at some point, so might as well do it now to get the king 
safe and rook into the game.} O-O {Black can play ...d6 and ...O-O in an 
interchangeable move-order.} 6. Re1 $1 {[%cal Ge1e5,Ge4d5,Bd7d5][%csl Re5] This 
is an important move to include. It might seem innocuous, but it is in fact 
simple prophylaxis against Black's possible idea of ...d5. Now with the e5-pawn 
under some sort of pressure (after ...d5 exd5), Black's central expansion 
aspirations have been thwarted.} d6 {Nothing too fancy - Black solidifies e5 and 
prepares to develop his bishop.} 7. a4 {[%cal Gc4a2,Bc2c3,Bb2b4][%csl Ga2]} 
({This is a strong, multi-purpose move which is White's most common choice 
together with} 7. c3 {. This move has two primary points to it:}) {1. White 
anticipates some ...Na5 manoeuvre. Black might want to gain the bishop pair like 
this, but now White has a retreat square on a2. 2. This move also is very useful 
in many cases. In this variation, Black tends to be very solid and well-placed 
in the centre, so White often shifts his attentions to the other flanks. a4, 
together with c3 and b4, form the basis for a possible space-gaining queenside 
expansion. Often Black finds the threat of a5-a6 so annoying and weakening that 
he stops it in its tracks with ...a5 (or ...a6).} Be6 {With this move Black 
invites an exchange of bishops as well as a change in pawn structure.} 8. Nbd2 
{[%cal Gd2c4][%csl Gc4]} ({Many less experienced players would jump at the 
opportunity to double Black's pawns, but in this case after} 8. Bxe6 fxe6 {the 
doubled pawns assist Black. The e6 pawn provides good central coverage and takes 
away White's typical outposts of e5 and f5 from his knights. In addition, Black 
would have the semi-open f-file to work with. Naturally, this all sounds pretty 
good for Black. Fortunately, there is no need to take on e6 quite yet. Instead 
we can support the bishop on c4 with our knight and keep playing.}) Qd7 {Black 
connects his rooks and gives himself the added possibility of recapturing on e6 
with the queen.} 9. c3 {[%cal Bb2b4,Bd3d4] A standard move, preparing both 
central and queenside play.} Rfe8 10. b4 $14 {[%cal Bd2f1,Bf1e3,Ba4a5,Bb4b5] 
White's extra space and possible pawn breaks offer him a slight edge. He can 
continue marching his queenside pawns forward or play for the d4-break. At some 
point, White might consider playing his knight to e3 via c4 (after Bxe6) or via 
f1.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Italian Game"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Italian Game 3..."]
[Black "Nf6 Mainline: 7... Na5"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-italian-game/course/4999, variation/179019"]

1. e4 {White's most popular first move attracts World champions and novices 
alike. Chess newcomers naturally gravitate towards it while many World 
Championships were decided by it. Fischer's move, together with 1. d4, has the 
simple plan of taking over the whole centre by playing d4 on the next move. In 
addition, it opens lines for White's bishop and queen, while preparing rapid 
development and kingside castling.} e5 {Black avoids the wild, unbalanced 
Sicilian or the exotic French and Caro-Kann and instead heads for the solid Open 
Games.} 2. Nf3 {A natural move - White attacks e5 and develops. By developing 
his kingside knight, White is one move closer to short castling.} Nc6 ({Black 
replies similarly - he covers the pawn and develops. However, Black has other 
options at his disposal - most notably} 2... Nf6 {, the Petroff Defence,}) 
({and} 2... d6 {, the Philidor Defence. Both of these openings will be covered 
in the final lines of this course.}) 3. Bc4 {The Italian Game is one of the 
oldest opening in chess and a staple amongst novice players. Despite this, it 
has recently been utilised by some of the top players in the World, including 
Magnus Carlsen. With 3. Bc4, White can expect to get a safe, positional game 
without being forced to learn all the theory in the Ruy Lopez. White's general 
plan is simple - central play with d4. It is important to note that this doesn't 
come immediately - instead White should prepare this pawn break with c3 and take 
his time in executing it. Often White will develop fully before setting his 
central pawns into motion.} ({From this position, Black has 2 main options:} 3. 
Bc4 3... Bc5) ({and} 3. Bc4 3... Nf6 {. The former usually leads to quiet 
positions while the later invites White to take play into the unorthodox with} 
4. Ng5 {.}) {First I will cover some rare deviations, such as 3... g6 and 3... 
Nd4. These are not very dangerous, but it is useful to have a vague idea of what 
to do against them. Other rare moves like 3... h6 and 3... Be7 are bound to 
transpose to the other lines I cover.} Nf6 ({This move is one of the two biggest 
challenges to the Italian game - together with 3 ...Bc5. While 3... Bc5 leads to 
tranquil waters, 3... Nf6 invites complications and imbalances if White obliges. 
White has 2 main choices here:} Nf6 4. d3) ({and} Nf6 4. Ng5 {.}) ({Other 
options such as} Nf6 4. d4) ({and} Nf6 4. Nc3 {are playable as well, but they 
are neither as challenging nor as popular as 4. d3 and 4. Ng5.}) 4. d3 ({For 
this repertoire my choice is 4. d3. The chief alternative,} 4. Ng5 {, was 
examined in depth but I discarded it for a few reasons:}) {1. It is too 
complicated and too theoretical for the purpose of this repertoire. 2. Black 
often relishes the wild positions after 4. Ng5 - he gets the chance to sacrifice 
a pawn for which he usually receives good compensation. 3. Finally, 4. d3 has 
the advantage of building a nice 'bridge' between Bc5 and Nf6. The positions can 
transpose and the structures are similar, meaning the plans and ideas are 
usually applicable to both lines. So, now that I've outlined my reasoning for my 
choice, let's take a look at the variations...} Be7 ({From this square Black's 
bishop is less active, but also less vulnerable than on c5. Both moves have 
their trumps, but in this variation play tends to develop along similar lines to 
the Ruy Lopez. Please note that} 4... Bc5 {would transpose to the ...Bc5 lines - 
refer to those lines for coverage of that move.}) 5. O-O {[%cal Bf1e1] We are 
going to castle at some point, so we might as well do it now to get the king 
safe and rook into the game.} O-O {Black can play ...d6 and ...O-O in an 
interchangeable move-order.} 6. Re1 $1 {This is an important move to include. It 
might seem innocuous, but it is in fact simple prophylaxis against Black's 
possible idea of ...d5. Now with the e5-pawn under some sort of pressure (after 
...d5 exd5), Black's central expansion aspirations have been thwarted.} d6 
{Nothing too fancy - Black solidifies e5 and prepares to develop his bishop.} 7. 
a4 ({This is a strong, multi-purpose move which is White's most common choice 
together with} 7. c3 {. This move has two primary points to it:}) {1. White 
anticipates some ...Na5 manoeuvre. Black might want to gain the bishop pair like 
this, but now White has a retreat square on a2. 2. This move also is very useful 
in many cases. In this variation, Black tends to be very solid and well-placed 
in the centre, so White often shifts his attentions to the other flanks. a4, 
together with c3 and b4, form the basis for a possible space-gaining queenside 
expansion. Often Black finds the threat of a5-a6 so annoying and weakening that 
he stops it in its tracks with ...a5 (or ...a6).} Na5 {[%cal Bc7c5][%csl Rc4] It 
might seem strange for Black to carry out his threat even when we spent our last 
move neutralising it. In fact, this move, which features often in the Ruy Lopez 
as well, has a clever point to it - Black isn't chasing the bishop merely for 
the sake of it - he rather is getting his knight out of the way so he can put a 
clamp on the centre with ...c5.} 8. Ba2 {[%csl Ga2,Gc1] There's no reason for 
White to surrender the bishop pair - so the bishop pulls back.} c5 {[%cal 
Gc5d4,Ge5d4][%csl Gd4] This is a standard plan in order to gain some space and 
prevent White's idea of d4 (at least for now).} 9. Na3 {[%cal 
Ba3c4,Bc4e3,Ge3d5,Ge3f5][%csl Gf5,Gd5] This is one of a handful of plans, but it 
is a fairly natural way to develop. Nbd2 blocks the bishop and Nc3 blocks the 
c-pawn, so this is fairly logical. White's grand plan is to bring the knight to 
e3 via c4 (or c2 once c3 has been played). From here it has great influence over 
the centre - in particular the d5 and f5 squares.} Nc6 {Now that Black has 
staked out his claim in the centre with ...c5, he retreats back to c6 with his 
knight - this is fairly standard in both the Ruy Lopez and Italian.} 10. c3 
{[%cal Bb2b4,Bd3d4] Controlling d4 and preparing to expand on the queenside.} h6 
{[%cal Gh6g5][%csl Gg5] Black rules out any possibility of Bg5 or Ng5. In 
addition, Black has the added possibility of a ...Nh7-g5 manoeuvre.} 11. Bd2 
{[%cal Bb2b4,Gd2b4] The bishop is well-placed here, where it supports the future 
b4 break. The seemingly-natural e3 square is sub-par because it obstructs the 
aforementioned plan of rerouting our knight to e3.} a6 {This was the suggestion 
of Ntirlis in 'Playing 1. e4 e5!'. The idea is to prepare queenside counterplay 
with ...Rb8 and ...b5. Without this, black could find himself in a position 
without easy counterplay. In certain situations, White might want to crack down 
on ...d5 breaks with c4 so that he may continue with kingside play.} 12. h3 $14 
{[%cal Ba3c4,Bc4e3,Bb2b4,Ba8b8,Bb7b5,Bf3h2,Bh2g4,Bg4f6,Ge3f5,Ge3d5][%csl 
Gg4,Gf5,Gd5] h3 is a standard, useful move preventing any g4 intrusions and 
providing future 'luft' for the king. We reach a fairly standard position for 
this variation which is very playable for both sides. Whether or not White has 
an advantage is debatable - if he does, it's very slight. Either way, I'd still 
choose White if given the chance. Play can develop in a number of ways from here 
for both sides. In a complicated position like this, with great winning chances 
for both sides, we must keep an eye out for the pawn breaks in the position - 
most notably ...b5 for Black and b4 for White. White's plan will typically 
involve a queenside/central expansion involving b4. The knight on a3 will be 
well-placed on e3 via c4. From there, a number of knight manoeuvres are 
possible, such as Nf3-h2-g4 (to trade off the f6-knight and gain access to d5) 
or Nh4-f5 (to control the f5 outpost). With good play, Black is bound to 
equalise - however, equal positions are far from draw and both sides have plenty 
of material here to work with.} *

