transpose and the structures are similar, meaning the plans and ideas are 
usually applicable to both lines. So, now that I've outlined my reasoning for my 
choice, let's take a look at the variations...} Be7 ({From this square Black's 
bishop is less active, but also less vulnerable than on c5. Both moves have 
their trumps, but in this variation play tends to develop along similar lines to 
the Ruy Lopez. Please note that} 4... Bc5 {would transpose to the ...Bc5 lines - 
refer to those lines for coverage of that move.}) 5. O-O {We are going to castle 
at some point, so we might as well do it now to get the king safe and rook into 
the game.} O-O {Black can play ...d6 and ...O-O in an interchangeable 
move-order.} 6. Re1 $1 {This is an important move to include. It might seem 
innocuous, but it is in fact simple prophylaxis against Black's possible idea of 
...d5. Now with the e5-pawn under some sort of pressure (after ...d5 exd5), 
Black's central expansion aspirations have been thwarted.} d6 {Nothing too fancy 
- Black solidifies e5 and prepares to develop his bishop.} 7. a4 ({This is a 
strong, multi-purpose move which is White's most common choice together with} 7. 
c3 {. This move has two primary points to it:}) {1. White anticipates some 
...Na5 manoeuvre. Black might want to gain the bishop pair like this, but now 
White has a retreat square on a2. 2. This move also is very useful in many 
cases. In this variation, Black tends to be very solid and well-placed in the 
centre, so White often shifts his attentions to the other flanks. a4, together 
with c3 and b4, form the basis for a possible space-gaining queenside expansion. 
Often Black finds the threat of a5-a6 so annoying and weakening that he stops it 
in its tracks with ...a5 (or ...a6).} Kh8 {[%cal Bf6g8,Bf7f5] This funny-looking 
move is not without some sense. Black steps out of the pin on the f7 pawn and 
prepares ...Ng8 followed by the ...f5 break.} 8. a5 {[%cal Ba5a6][%csl Rb7] 
White's idea is the standard a6 to soften up Black's queenside.} a6 ({Black 
naturally shouldn't allow that - after something like} 8... Ng8 9. a6 b6 {White 
can target Black's light-squared weaknesses on the queenside.}) 9. h3 {This is a 
clever wait-and-see strategy which will be explained in a couple of moves - the 
immediate c3 + d4 is also good, but it runs into some complications which I 
thought best be avoided for this course.} Ng8 {Black intends to follow-through 
with his plan of ...f5.} 10. Nc3 $1 {[%cal Bc3d5][%csl Gd5] White switches plans 
- no more c3 and d4 on the cards (for now)! Instead our intention is to exploit 
the missing knight on f6 - our knight is heading to the d5 outpost! From there 
it is possible to pick up the bishop pair (by taking on e7) whenever we want.} 
f5 {Finally, Black has executed his plan - unfortunately for him, it doesn't 
have all that much impact.} 11. Nd5 {[%csl Re7] Our knight lands on d5 - a great 
outpost where it surveys the whole board. Additionally, should our knight ever 
get ousted, we have the option of gaining the bishop pair by playing Nxe7.} fxe4 
12. dxe4 $14 {[%cal Gd5e7,Bb2b4,Bc2c3,Bb4b5][%csl Gd5,Re7] Black's ...f5 break 
hasn't achieved that much. We are left with a strong knight on d5 and a 
queenside space advantage. White should take some care regarding his king - if 
we're not careful Black might whip up a kingside attack. Otherwise, White should 
strive to play on the queenside with a longterm goal of b4-b5.} *

